description:
Add --format zod to generate a Zod schema instead of plain .d.ts or runtime validator. This bridges esk to the t3-env ecosystem â€” users get a schema they can plug directly into createEnv().

Output:
  import { z } from "zod";

  export const envSchema = z.object({
    STRIPE_KEY: z.string(),
    DATABASE_URL: z.string(),
  });

  export type Env = z.infer<typeof envSchema>;

This is the #1 requested pattern from t3-env users. Could later extend to valibot/arktype via --format valibot, --format arktype.

Add --preset flag that bundles common framework conventions:

  esk generate --preset next    # client_prefix=NEXT_PUBLIC_, outputs to env.d.ts
  esk generate --preset nuxt    # client_prefix=NUXT_PUBLIC_, outputs to env.d.ts
  esk generate --preset vite    # client_prefix=VITE_, outputs to env.d.ts
  esk generate --preset astro   # client_prefix=PUBLIC_, outputs to env.d.ts

Each preset would configure:
- Client prefix for server/client splitting (depends on esk-k9a)
- Sensible default output path
- Framework-specific augmentation target (e.g. Vite uses ImportMetaEnv not NodeJS.ProcessEnv)

Vite example:
  interface ImportMetaEnv {
    readonly VITE_API_URL: string;
  }
  interface ImportMeta {
    readonly env: ImportMetaEnv;
  }

Reduces friction for the most common setups.

SecretDef already has an optional description field. Include it as JSDoc comments in generated TypeScript output.

Before:
  STRIPE_KEY: string;

After:
  /** Stripe API key */
  STRIPE_KEY: string;

Same for runtime mode â€” add JSDoc above each property in the env object. Free documentation from existing config data.
